Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This dataset contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue, the dataset has the following columns :

  • id : tmdb id
  • imdb-id : id in the imdb site
  • popularity : popularity percentage
  • budget : budget written in full
  • revenue : reveneu written in full
  • original_title : original movie title
  • cast : most notable cast members
  • homepage : homepage address of the movie
  • director : director name
  • tagline : most notable tagline from the movie
  • keywords : keywords related to the movie
  • overview : a breif describtion of the movie
  • runtime : movie runtime in minutes
  • genres : genres the movie falls under
  • production_company : production company of the movie
  • release_date : release date of the movie month/day/year
  • vote_count : number of voters
  • vote_average : average rating of the movie
  • release_year : release year
  • budget_adj : budget in exponent form

  • revenue_adj : revenue in exponent form

    ### Question(s) for Analysis

Is there a trend or effect on revenue based on release date ? If there is a trend or effect:

  • Which quarter of the year performs generally better relative to movies of the same rating range ?

  • Do movies - of the same group -meaning same rating rounded to the closest integer- released in the first half of a month -when most people have most of their salary still intact- perform better in terms of revenue than those released in the latter half ?

  • Do movies -same relative criteria mention above- released later in the month get a bit less rating in thier relative rating group -like from 7 to 8, 8 to 9 and so on- ?

the problem is caused by having rows with zeros as values for budget and revenue, so it didn't appear as a problem when checking with df.info() because these rows had zeros for values in budget and revenue columns, but when we made the new revenue_ratio column this resulted in a problem because of the devision of zeros

a possible solution would be to fill them with the mean budget and revenue but that woudn't be very accurate and for my specific analysis questions I need more accurate results for each rating group (6 to 7, 7 to 8 ..... and so on), so we are going to fill each group by the mean revenue and budget of this group not the entire dataframe.

we will do that by:

  1. creating new dataframes or more accuratley masked dataframes for each rating group starting from the minimum rating in the dataframe

  2. dropping rows that have null values in the revenue_ratio columns as an indicator for the rows that have zeros for revenue and budget

  3. then we get the mean revenue and budget for these rows

  4. filling the rows that have zeros as values for revenue and budget columns with the mean of each group by appying the condition that we used to create the masked dataframes on top of the having zeros as values codition

In [115]:
# create lists to hold counts of movies in each rating group before and after the adjustments
group_amounts_before = []
group_amounts = []
df['rating_group'] = df['vote_average']
# fill the rows with zeros in revenue and budget columns with mean revenue and mean budget for each group
for i in range(1, 10):
    # create a temporary dataframe to hold filtered results for each cycle 
    trimmed_df = df[(df['vote_average']<i+1) & (df['vote_average']>=i) & (df['revenue']!=0) & (df['budget']!=0)]
    # append the number of rows 
    group_amounts_before.append(trimmed_df.shape[0])

    # create a trimmed dataframe to only include revenue to get the mean revenue of each group as cycles go by
    trimmed_df_revenue = trimmed_df['revenue'] 
    # create a trimmed dataframe to only include budget to get the mean revenue of each group as cycles go by
    trimmed_df_budget = trimmed_df['budget']
    
    # fill rows that have zeros with means for each group as cycles go by 
    df['revenue'].mask((df['vote_average']<i+1) & (df['vote_average']>=i) & (df['revenue']==0) & (df['budget']==0), trimmed_df_revenue.mean(), inplace=True)
    df['budget'].mask((df['vote_average']<i+1) & (df['vote_average']>=i) & (df['revenue']==0) & (df['budget']==0), trimmed_df_budget.mean(), inplace=True)
    df['rating_group'].mask((df['vote_average']<i+1) & (df['vote_average']>=i), 'r{}to{}'.format(i,i+1), inplace=True)
    trimmed_df = df[(df['vote_average']<i+1) & (df['vote_average']>=i)]
    group_amounts.append(trimmed_df.shape[0])

# edit the revenue_ratio column after the new adjustments
df['revenue_ratio'] = df['revenue'] / df['budget']

we also added a new column called rating_group for later use

# creat a function for sns plotting to reduce repeatative code in later use
def plotter (df, x_axis, y_axis, kind, label_name_x, label_name_y, title) :
    """
    makes sns bar or strip plots.

    Aargs:
        (dataframe) df - dataframe to use
        (str) x_axis - name of the colunm in the dataframe to use as the x axis
        (str) y_axis - name of the colunm in the dataframe to use as the y axis
        (str) kind - type of plot to be made
        (str) label_name_x - name to use for the x axis
        (str) label_name_y - name to use for the y axis
        (str) title - name to use as title for the plot
    returns:
        plot - a plot with the specified type and features
    """
    
    if kind == 'bar' :
        plot = sns.barplot(x = x_axis, y=y_axis, data=df)
        plot.set(xlabel=label_name_x, ylabel=label_name_y, title=title)
        return plot
        
    elif kind == 'strip' :
        plot = sns.stripplot(x = x_axis, y=y_axis, data=df)
        plot.set(xlabel=label_name_x, ylabel=label_name_y, title=title)
        return plot

    trimmed_df_budget = temporary_df['budget']
    # append data to its intended list

# specify months, weeks, quarters to be looped over later
months = df['release_month_name'].unique()
weeks = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
quarters = [1, 2, 3, 4]

# creat a placeholder in the appropriate dictionary for each month of release for each of the wanted stats
for month in months :
    data_r['{}_mean'.format(month)]=[]
    data_b['{}_mean'.format(month)]=[]

# create a placeholder in the appropriate dictionary for each week of release
for week in weeks :
    data_weeks['{}_mean'.format(week)]=[]

# create a placeholder in the appropriate dictionary for each quarter
for quarter in quarters :
    data_quarters['{}_mean'.format(quarter)]=[]
    
# loop over months, weeks, quarters for each cycle in range of the wanted rating groups
for i in range (2,9) :
    for month in months :
        data_r['{}_mean'.format(month)].append(df.revenue[(df['release_month_name']==month) & (df['vote_average']<i+1) & (df['vote_average']>=i)].mean())
        data_b['{}_mean'.format(month)].append(df.budget[(df['release_month_name']==month) & (df['vote_average']<i+1) & (df['vote_average']>=i)].mean())
    for week in weeks :
        data_weeks['{}_mean'.format(week)].append(df.revenue[(df['week_of_month']==week) & (df['vote_average']<i+1) & (df['vote_average']>=i)].mean())
    for quarter in quarters :
        data_quarters['{}_mean'.format(quarter)].append(df.revenue[(df['quarter']==quarter) & (df['vote_average']<i+1) & (df['vote_average']>=i)].mean())

Conclusions¶

after inspecting the revenue of movies for each month, quarter, week and for each rating group it was found that:

  1. there are some trends in movie performance based on release date
  2. the best performing quarter for the movies with the biggest revenues and the highest rating is the last quarter of the year
  3. the best performing quarted for most movies is the 2nd quarter of the year
  4. the start of the month is the best performing period for the highest rated movies
  5. the second half of the month is generally the best performing period for most movies
  6. there is no visible trend in ratings in realtion to release weeks

Limitations¶

there aren't enough samples of high rated movies and some samples -1 to 2 rating & 9 to 10 rating- had no enough correct data -budget and mean- to calculate the mean for its rating group and fill zero values with, and filling

further research¶

further research could be done with:

  1. more samples of high and low rated movies
  2. data on what regions make what percentage of the revenue
  3. data on some user info for the accounts that rated the movie like age

in the areas of:

  • the performance of top rated actors across multiple movie genres
  • the performance of certain geners in certain national or international holidays & events -like how much more do romance movies make in valentine's day and how much better do horror movies perfoem in halloween season- , and in the case of international holidays & events :
    • what regions show the most correlation
    • the population of each region
    • extra info on the accounts of users who rate like age which could be really helpful in many areas like measuring the effect of certain genres on certain age groups and determining best launch windows based on work conditions across the globe for the most enthusiastic age group for each genre
